{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658270"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:45:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:45:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20724"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20724"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.13,0.73,0.05,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95806"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13600"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78585"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10956"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11791"},{"type":"tags","id":"12602"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32701"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32702"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95806"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic inflammation is a prolonged host response to persistent stimuli such as infections, autoimmune reactions, or toxic substances. While acute inflammation typically resolves once the injurious agent is eliminated, chronic inflammation can persist for months to years, leading to tissue damage and fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a mechanism involved in the termination of chronic inflammatory responses?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recruitment of additional neutrophils to the site of injury","Increased production of pro-inflammatory cytokines","Macrophage clearance of apoptotic neutrophils","Activation of the classical complement pathway","Upregulation of adhesion molecules on endothelial cells"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Emacrophage clearance of apoptotic neutrophils\u003C/strong\u003E. This process, known as efferocytosis, is a critical step in the resolution of inflammation. When macrophages engulf apoptotic neutrophils, they switch from a pro-inflammatory to an anti-inflammatory phenotype, producing mediators such as transforming growth factor-beta (TGF-\u03b2) and interleukin-10 (IL-10) that suppress inflammation. This process also prevents the release of toxic contents from neutrophils that would otherwise occur during necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecruitment of additional neutrophils to the site of injury\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a characteristic of ongoing inflammation, not its resolution. Neutrophil recruitment is an early event in acute inflammation that can contribute to tissue damage if persistent.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased production of pro-inflammatory cytokines\u003C/strong\u003E - This promotes and sustains inflammation rather than terminating it. Pro-inflammatory cytokines like IL-1, IL-6, and TNF-\u03b1 amplify the inflammatory response.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of the classical complement pathway\u003C/strong\u003E - This generates inflammatory mediators and promotes leukocyte recruitment, contributing to inflammation rather than its resolution.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUpregulation of adhesion molecules on endothelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This facilitates leukocyte adhesion and migration into tissues, promoting inflammation rather than resolving it.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important mechanisms in the resolution of chronic inflammation include the production of specialised pro-resolving mediators (SPMs) derived from polyunsaturated fatty acids, such as lipoxins, resolvins, and protectins; the inhibition of pro-inflammatory signalling pathways; and the clearance of inflammatory stimuli. Failure of these resolution mechanisms can lead to persistent inflammation and associated pathologies including fibrosis, tissue destruction, and functional impairment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic inflammation resolution requires elimination of the injurious agent, suppression of inflammatory mediators, and clearance of inflammatory cells.","Macrophages play a crucial role in inflammation resolution by clearing apoptotic neutrophils (efferocytosis) and producing anti-inflammatory cytokines.","Specialised pro-resolving mediators (SPMs) derived from polyunsaturated fatty acids actively promote resolution of inflammation.","Failure of inflammation resolution leads to persistent tissue damage, fibrosis, and chronic inflammatory diseases."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 101"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78585"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20724"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78585"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-29T20:14:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-29T20:15:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13600"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95806"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{